## Shifting From Frameworks to People

The first ten days of this challenge were heavy on frameworks — NIST RMF, HIPAA, ISO 27001, PCI DSS. All of that was necessary and genuinely useful. But today felt like a different kind of important. Because frameworks do not implement themselves. Policies do not write themselves. Risk assessments do not happen automatically. Behind every GRC program that actually works, there are people with defined roles, clear responsibilities, and the ability to collaborate across functions.

Today I tried to understand who those people are, what they do, and honestly — where someone like me might fit in all of this.

---

## What I Worked On Today

GRC programs in healthcare organizations typically involve several distinct roles. In large organizations these are separate people with separate teams. In smaller organizations — like a community clinic running OpenMRS — one person might cover two or three of these responsibilities simultaneously. What matters is not the org chart but that every responsibility is actually owned by someone.

Here are the key roles I studied today:

---

### CISO — Chief Information Security Officer

The CISO sits at the top of the security function and is responsible for the overall security strategy of the organization. They translate business goals and regulatory requirements into security policies, oversee risk management programs, and make sure that security is represented at the leadership level.

In a large hospital system the CISO might lead a team of dozens. In a small clinic using OpenMRS, the equivalent might be an IT Director who is wearing the CISO hat alongside several other responsibilities. The title matters less than the function: someone needs to own the security direction of the organization and have the authority to act on it.

What I found interesting about this role is how much of it is communication rather than technical work. A CISO who cannot explain risk to a board of directors or justify security investment to a CFO will struggle to get anything done — no matter how technically skilled they are. That is a pattern I keep noticing in GRC: the most important skills are often judgment, communication, and the ability to connect security decisions to organizational outcomes.

---

### Risk Manager

The Risk Manager is responsible for identifying, assessing, and tracking risks across the organization. They maintain the risk register, coordinate risk assessments with IT and clinical teams, and make sure that identified risks are being actively managed rather than just documented.

In the context of OpenMRS, the Risk Manager would be the person asking: what are the realistic threats to this system? What vulnerabilities exist? If something goes wrong, what is the impact on patient care? They are the person who makes sure the organization has an honest picture of its risk environment — not an optimistic one.

This is the role I find myself most drawn to so far in this challenge. There is something about the combination of analytical thinking, cross-functional collaboration, and the need to communicate findings clearly that feels like a natural fit for how I approach problems. I am still learning — but this is the direction I want to grow.

---

### Compliance Officer

The Compliance Officer is responsible for ensuring the organization meets its regulatory obligations — HIPAA, HITECH, state privacy laws, and any other applicable requirements. They manage documentation, conduct staff training, perform internal audits, and act as the point of contact when regulators come asking questions.

What I found interesting about this role today is how much it depends on relationships. A Compliance Officer who only enforces rules from a distance will struggle to build the kind of culture where people actually follow them. The most effective compliance programs I have read about involve compliance officers who work closely with clinical and technical teams — explaining why requirements exist, not just that they exist.

The tension between compliance and security that I wrote about on Day 4 often plays out at the level of these roles. The Compliance Officer is responsible for meeting the regulatory floor. The CISO is responsible for building security above that floor. Getting those two functions aligned — rather than pulling in different directions — is one of the most important coordination challenges in healthcare GRC.

---

### System Owner

The System Owner is responsible for the day-to-day security and operational posture of a specific system. In this project that system is OpenMRS. The System Owner makes decisions about configuration, access control, patching schedules, and what happens when something goes wrong.

This role is important because it provides accountability at the system level rather than the organizational level. The CISO sets the policy. The System Owner implements it for their specific system and is responsible for keeping it aligned with that policy over time.

In a small clinic, the System Owner might be the same person as the IT Manager — someone who knows OpenMRS well, understands the clinical workflows it supports, and has the technical ability to configure and maintain it securely.

---

### Authorizing Official (AO)

The Authorizing Official is a senior executive — a Clinic Director, CEO, or equivalent — who formally accepts the residual risk of operating a system and authorizes it to go live. This role comes directly from the NIST RMF framework I covered on Day 6.

What I find significant about this role is what it represents: a named senior leader who has reviewed the security findings, understands the risks that remain, and is willing to put their name on the decision to proceed. That is not a rubber stamp — it is a genuine accountability mechanism. If something goes wrong after authorization, there is a documented record of who reviewed the risk and what they accepted.

In an OpenMRS deployment, the AO might be the Medical Director or the Executive Director of the organization. They are not expected to be technical experts — but they are expected to understand the risk picture well enough to make an informed decision.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most today is how much GRC depends on coordination between these roles rather than any one of them working in isolation.

A Risk Manager who identifies a critical vulnerability but cannot get the CISO to prioritize it has not managed the risk. A Compliance Officer who documents HIPAA requirements but cannot get the System Owner to implement the controls has not achieved compliance. An Authorizing Official who approves a system without a meaningful briefing from the risk team has not made a real risk decision.

GRC works when these roles communicate well, when responsibilities are clearly defined, and when findings from one function actually inform decisions in another. It breaks down when people work in silos — which, from everything I have read, is far more common than the ideal.

---

## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the aftermath of the **2015 Office of Personnel Management (OPM) breach** — one of the largest breaches of US government data in history, affecting over 21 million people. Congressional investigations and post-incident reviews identified a pattern of GRC role failures that contributed to the breach.

Among the findings: the organization's IT security roles were not clearly defined, risk assessments had not been conducted on key systems, and system authorizations had been granted to systems that had not been properly assessed. In other words, the people and roles that should have been providing oversight were either absent, under-resourced, or not communicating effectively with each other.

What I took from that: the OPM breach was not primarily a technical failure. It was an organizational and governance failure. The NIST RMF framework that the agency was supposed to be following — including the Authorize step with a named Authorizing Official — existed precisely to prevent this kind of gap. But having a framework on paper and actually operationalizing it through people with clear roles and accountability are two very different things.

That example made today's topic feel much more concrete and much more consequential than a list of job titles would suggest.

