## Where I See Myself in This

I want to be honest about where I am right now. I do not have formal professional experience in any of these roles yet. That is part of why I am doing this challenge — to build the knowledge and demonstrate the thinking that would qualify me to step into one of them.

The role I am most drawn to is Risk Manager. The work of identifying what could go wrong, assessing it honestly, communicating it clearly, and tracking whether it is being addressed feels like a natural fit for how I think. It is also a role where the skills I am building through this project — risk assessment, framework knowledge, written communication — are directly applicable.

I also find the System Owner role interesting in the context of this project specifically. Going through 100 days of securing OpenMRS on AWS is essentially practicing what a System Owner does — understanding the system deeply, making security decisions, and documenting the reasoning behind them.

---

## What I Am Still Thinking About

One thing I keep wondering: in organizations where GRC roles are not formally defined — which is common in smaller healthcare settings — how do you make the case for defining them? The value of role clarity is obvious once something goes wrong. But before that, it can feel like unnecessary overhead to leadership that is already stretched thin.

Is there a practical way to introduce role definition incrementally — starting with the most critical responsibilities — without requiring a full organizational restructuring? I think the answer is probably yes, but I want to think more carefully about what that looks like in practice.

